{"eventId":"evt_ctea_001","eventType":"claim_first_seen","claimId":"clm_ctea_001","fromRevisionId":1280000201,"toRevisionId":1280000202,"section":"Background","before":"","after":"The Copyright Term Extension Act (CTEA), also known as the Sonny Bono Copyright Term Extension Act, was signed into law by President Bill Clinton on October 27, 1998. The act extended copyright terms in the United States by 20 years, harmonizing US law with the European Union's Directive 93/98/EEC.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The basic factual claim about the CTEA's passage date and extension length first appeared in this revision.","detail":"Added with citation to Public Law 105-298 and the EU Copyright Term Directive (93/98/EEC)."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Established the baseline legislative fact set for the article.","confidence":0.96,"discussionType":"legislative_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-01-10T09:15:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_002","eventType":"claim_reworded","claimId":"clm_ctea_001a","fromRevisionId":1280000203,"toRevisionId":1280000204,"section":"Background","before":"The act extended copyright terms in the United States by 20 years, harmonizing US law with the European Union's Directive 93/98/EEC.","after":"The act extended copyright terms for works published after 1923: existing copyrights were extended from 75 to 95 years for corporate authorship, and from life-plus-50 to life-plus-70 years for individual authorship. The extension was intended to align US law with the European Union's 1993 Copyright Term Directive, which had adopted life-plus-70 years as the standard.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded to specify the pre-existing terms (75 years for corporate, life+50 for individual) alongside the new terms (95 years and life+70).","detail":"Added specific term durations with citations to the 1976 Copyright Act (Title 17, pre-CTEA) and the CTEA amendments (Pub. L. 105-298)."},{"fact":"The EU harmonization rationale was clarified to note that the EU adopted life+70 in 1993, creating a term differential that the CTEA was designed to close.","detail":"Editor cited the Directive's 1995 implementation deadline and the Berne Convention's national-treatment principle."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Improved precision from a one-sentence summary to a term-by-term specification with legislative context.","confidence":0.91,"discussionType":"factual_clarification"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-02-05T11:22:45Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_003","eventType":"talk_thread_opened","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000205,"toRevisionId":1280000206,"section":"Talk:Copyright Term Extension Act","before":"","after":"The article currently frames the CTEA exclusively through a US legislative lens. Given that the law was explicitly motivated by EU Directive 93/98/EEC, shouldn't the 'Background' section include a paragraph on the EU directive's adoption and the international harmonization context? Several editors have also noted that the article should discuss whether the term 'harmonization' is neutral (WP:NPOV) when some scholars characterize it as an upward ratchet.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A new talk page thread titled 'NPOV: harmonization vs. ratchet framing' was opened.","detail":"Started by user IPPolicyScholar on 2024-03-18T14:55:20Z."},{"fact":"The thread raises two concerns: (1) the EU directive context is underdeveloped, (2) the term 'harmonization' may violate NPOV.","detail":"The editor cited Nimmer (2000) and Lessig (2004) as scholars who contest the 'harmonization' characterization."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Opened a dual dispute about international scope and framing neutrality on a policy page.","confidence":0.74,"discussionType":"neutrality_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-03-18T14:55:20Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_004","eventType":"citation_replaced","claimId":"clm_ctea_002","fromRevisionId":1280000207,"toRevisionId":1280000208,"section":"Constitutional challenge","before":"In Eldred v. Ashcroft (2003), the Supreme Court upheld the CTEA against constitutional challenges under the Copyright Clause and the First Amendment. [12]","after":"In Eldred v. Ashcroft, 537 U.S. 186 (2003), the Supreme Court upheld the CTEA in a 7-2 decision. Justice Ginsburg, writing for the majority, held that the Copyright Clause gives Congress discretion over copyright term and does not require a 'quid pro quo' test linking term length to the promotion of progress. Justice Breyer dissented, arguing that the 20-year extension was effectively perpetual on an economic basis and violated the Copyright Clause's 'limited Times' restriction. Justice Stevens also dissented. [12][18]","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"New citation [18] was added: the official Supreme Court slip opinion for Eldred v. Ashcroft, 537 U.S. 186.","detail":"The previous citation [12] was a CRS summary. The replacement provides primary-source attribution to the controlling opinion and both dissents."},{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a one-sentence outcome to a summary of the majority and dissenting rationales.","detail":"The Ginsburg majority focuses on the Copyright Clause's discretion argument; the Breyer dissent focuses on 'effectively perpetual' economic analysis."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Upgraded a legal holding summary from news-media paraphrase to primary-source analysis with both concurring and dissenting views.","confidence":0.93,"policyDimension":"verifiability","discussionType":"citation_strengthening"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-04-25T16:30:10Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_005","eventType":"section_reorganized","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000209,"toRevisionId":1280000210,"section":"Criticism","before":"(Section contained a single undifferentiated list of 14 opposition arguments)","after":"(Section reorganized with subheadings: 'The constitutional argument (limited times)', 'The economic argument (orphan works and deadweight loss)', 'The public domain argument (cultural access)', and 'The Eldred aftermath')","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The flat list of 14 criticisms was reorganized into 4 thematic subheadings.","detail":"The reorganization was proposed on the talk page by user IPPolicyScholar and adopted after 12 replies showed consensus."},{"fact":"The 'Eldred aftermath' subheading was new, consolidating material from 3 other sections that discussed legislative responses to the Eldred decision.","detail":"This included the Public Domain Enhancement Act (2003, not passed), the Orrin Hatch 'copyright perpetuity' proposal, and state-level public domain advocacy."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Structural improvement transforming an undifferentiated critique dump into a thematically organized analysis of distinct legal and policy arguments.","confidence":0.81,"discussionType":"structure_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-05-15T10:40:33Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_006","eventType":"revert_detected","claimId":"clm_ctea_003","fromRevisionId":1280000211,"toRevisionId":1280000212,"section":"Legislative history","before":"The act was strongly supported by the Walt Disney Company, whose copyright on Mickey Mouse (Steamboat Willie, 1928) was approaching expiration. Disney spent an estimated $6.3 million on lobbying for the extension.","after":"The act was strongly supported by the Walt Disney Company, whose copyright on Mickey Mouse (Steamboat Willie, 1928) was approaching expiration. Disney spent an estimated $6.3 million on lobbying for the extension.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Revision 1280000211 was an exact revert of revision 1280000210.","detail":"An editor had prepended 'Derisively nicknamed the Mickey Mouse Protection Act by critics,' to the beginning of the paragraph. The revert was performed by moderator PolicyEditor with summary: 'rv — nickname is well-documented but belongs in the 'Criticism' section with attribution, not in the lede of Legislative history.'"}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restored neutral tone in the Legislative history section after a pejorative nickname was inserted in wiki voice.","confidence":0.94,"policyDimension":"neutrality","discussionType":"edit_revert"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-06-20T09:15:40Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_007","eventType":"claim_strengthened","claimId":"clm_ctea_004","fromRevisionId":1280000213,"toRevisionId":1280000214,"section":"Background","before":"The CTEA was the eleventh extension of copyright terms enacted by Congress since 1790.","after":"The CTEA was the eleventh extension of copyright terms enacted by Congress since the original Copyright Act of 1790, which granted a 14-year term with a single 14-year renewal. By the time of the CTEA, the maximum term had grown from 28 years to 95 years for corporate works and life-plus-70 for individual works—a 239% increase in maximum term length over the nation's first two centuries.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded to include the specific timeline progression (14+14 → 95/life+70) and a percentage calculation.","detail":"Editor added citations to the 1790, 1831, 1909, 1976, and 1998 acts with term-length calculations."},{"fact":"A 239% increase figure was introduced, calculated from the 1790 maximum (28 years) to the 1998 maximum for corporate works (95 years).","detail":"The percentage was attributed to Sprigman (2004) in the Cardozo Arts & Entertainment Law Journal."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Upgraded from a bare count to a quantified trajectory analysis with specific historical reference points.","confidence":0.87,"discussionType":"historical_context"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-08-12T14:25:15Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_ctea_008","eventType":"talk_thread_archived","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000215,"toRevisionId":1280000216,"section":"Talk:Copyright Term Extension Act","before":"(Active thread: 'NPOV: harmonization vs. ratchet framing' with 31 replies over 5 months)","after":"(Thread resolved with consensus to present both 'harmonization' and 'upward ratchet' framings in the Background section with attribution to their respective scholarly advocates)","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The NPOV thread was closed with a compromise resolution after 5 months of discussion.","detail":"The consensus: the Background section now reads 'The CTEA was enacted to bring US law into alignment with the European Union's 1993 directive—a process proponents described as harmonization and critics characterized as an upward ratchet extending copyright globally.'"},{"fact":"The compromise text was drafted by IPPolicyScholar and adopted after receiving 19 supporting replies from 8 unique editors.","detail":"This represents a textbook case of structured NPOV resolution through dual-attribution framing."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Resolved a neutrality dispute through the canonical Wikipedia NPOV technique of attributing contested framings to their respective proponents.","confidence":0.83,"discussionType":"dispute_resolution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-09-28T11:00:00Z"}
